\cf0 Subheading: History of the game\
\
Body: Jig is based on a folk game called Fish, which is played with a standard deck of cards and likely named because it sounds a bit like you\'92re playing the children\'92s game Go Fish (instead of \'93Do you have any 2s?\'94, a player might ask \'93Do you have the 2 of clubs?\'94). There seems to be no written record of Fish; it was introduced to the author at McGill University in the early 2000s. \
\
The original game had some drawbacks, including the challenge of defining 8 or 9 equal sets in a standard deck of cards. Jig was created to solve this problem, with a custom deck of nine coloured sets, so that we could share this addictive little game with the world. It also introduces a 4-player variant and an optional \'93shark\'94 rule for ultra-competitive players. \
\
The name is a nod to the original: \'93jigging\'94 is a traditional fishing method in Newfoundland and Labrador. The jigger hook and wooden reel are treasured symbols of the province\'92s fishing heritage.\
